		<h1>the venue</h1>
		<p>Dos Pueblos Ranch was home to one of the largest groups of Native Americans in California, the Canalinos. Juan Cabrillo set his anchor directly off the coast of the ranch&#8217;s beach in 1542, saw the two settlements of Native Americans on either side of the river canyon and called it Los Dos Pueblos &#8212; The Two Villages. The name has stuck ever since.</p>
		<p></p>
		<p>Over the years, Dos Pueblos has been a cattle ranch, a horse ranch, an orchid farm, a honey farm and is currently an avocado and cheremoya farm. The land is historical and the beaches are preserved. We are honored to get married at such an amazing place and share it with all of you.</p>
		<p><strong style="color:purple"> *A note for the ladies...the ground is dirt and grass, so we recommend wearing wedges, sandals or a thicker heel.</strong></p>

